age)?<br /><br />No. Because a PageSwapCache() page should be a perfectly normal page<br />cache thing. It will increment the page count if it's active.<br /><br />That PageKsm() thing that *doesn't* increment the page could does look<br />worrisome, but<br /><br />&gt; So we check page_count() (which covers KSM or normal pages) after we've got the<br />&gt; page lock, while we keep all the rest.<br /><br />Why would we keep the rest? I<br /><br />The actual thing I would really want to get rid of is the page lock,<br />in fact. We shouldn't need it in this path, and it's the most<br />expensive part of it all. But that's also why I did the page count<br />test optimistically unlocked - because if page_count is 1, then we<br />really shouldn't contend with anything else, so hopefully the<br />(currently quite expensive) page locking is actually a non-issue once<br />you get there.<br /><br />But the PageKsm() page_count() issue I didn't even realize. That worries me.<br /><br />                Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
